Who'll be the Next Soccer Star?¶

CMSC320 Data Science Final Project¶

By: Erin Halper and Maggie Zhou¶

Introduction¶

This tutorial focuses on the FIFA 2021 EA Sports video game data. The game was released October 2020, and the data contains information about the players for the 2021 year. The ultimate goal of the tutorial is to gain a better understanding of the information regarding the players in the FIFA 2021 data. This includes getting an understanding of what the distribution looks like some of the features included in the data as well as seeing how some of the features relate to each other in discovering any fascinating trends. We are hoping that finding patterns in the data will reveal information about what differentiates higher ranked players versus lower ranked players. We will analyze the features to learn about their relationships with each other as well as how they affect a player’s rank. We want to see how this kind of data can be used to predict the skill of future players and consider how future players would rank based on the features available in this data set. An important consideration is that this data is only from the 2021 year, so it would be necessary to conduct analyses from many other years as well in order to make generalizations to all FIFA data and for making future predictions. This tutorial will however have the main focus on the 2021 FIFA data with the goal of discovering existing patterns and trends in the current 2021 data.

Specifically, this data set contains all of male soccer players from the FIFA 2021 video game. The data set has 17981 players (rows) and 9 columns. The columns included in the data that will used in the analysis are name, nationality, position, overall, age, and team. Let’s break down what each of these columns mean.

-name - the full name of each player as -first last- (17981 total players in data set)    
-nationality - country the player is from and the international team they play for (162 total nationalities represented in data set)   
-position - position(s) the player plays, separated by by ‘|’ if they play multiple (15 positions are LW, ST, RWB, LB, CM, LWB, CB, CAM, GK, RW, CDM, RB, LM, RM, CF)     
-overall - rank of the player in the videogame, ranging from 56 to 94 where better players are given higher numbered ranks     
-age - age of the player as of 2021, ranges from 17 to 43     
-team - club team that the player plays for as of 2021 (713 total clubs in data set)

What is overall rank based on? https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/fifa-player-ratings-explained-how-are-the-card-number-stats/1hszd2fgr7wgf1n2b2yjdpgynu

The data set can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/aayushmishra1512/fifa-2021-complete-player-data

These are the Python libraries we will be using to conduct the analysis.

Data Collection¶

First, we will download the data and put them into two dataframes. We will be getting our data from two sources. The main source of our data will be stored in a dataframe called 'data' and contains all the information about the FIFA players. The second source of the data we will be using will be stored in a dataframe called 'loc'. The 'loc' dataframe is temporary as we will only be using it to get the latitude and longitude data for each country represented in the FIFA data. We will be transferring the latitudes and longitudes over to a new dataframe in the next step. The latitudes and longitudes will be utilized for displaying trends on maps during the Exploratory Analysis and Data Visualization phase.

Data Tidying, Cleaning, & Refining¶

Next, we will need to add a new column to the main 'data' dataframe to help ease the analysis. A column called, 'continent' will be added which will correspond to the nationality's continent. This will allow us to compare data according to continent as well. We can also get rid of some of the columns that we will not be using for this project. We will delete the 'player_id', 'potential', and 'hits' columns.

As mentioned above, the 'loc' dataframe was temporary, and a new dataframe called 'countries' will be created to hold summarized information for each country including taking the latitude and longitude data from the 'loc' dataframe for the countries that are included. Not all of the nationalities represented in the FIFA data (in 'data') are included in the 'loc' data, so we will have to input the latitudes and longitudes manually for those countries.

We will make a new dataframe called 'countries' that will store summarized information about each country represented in the FIFA data (from nationality column). It will have the following columns: country, latitude, longitude, average age, average rank, and number of players included in this data set. The latitudes and longitudes will be retrieved from the 'loc' dataframe that we got data from above. Not all of the nationalities represented in the FIFA data are included in the 'loc' data, so we will have to manually input their corresponding coordinate values for the countries that do not have their coordinates provided.

#Adds all of the latitude and longitude data for all countries to the new 'countries' dataframe

#Make a new dataframe that will hold information for all countries
#including their latitude, longitude. Will also have columns for average age, average rank, and number of players in the dataset with nationality of that country
countries = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["country", "lat", "long", "avgAge", "avgRank", "numPlayers"])

uniqueCountries = set()
#Go through FIFA data and get full set of countries represented under 'nationality' column
for i in data.index:
    if data.at[i, "nationality"] not in uniqueCountries:
        uniqueCountries.add(data.at[i, "nationality"])
        countries = countries.append({"country": data.at[i, "nationality"], "lat": "-", "long": "-",
            "avgAge": "-", "avgRank": "-", "numPlayers": "-"}, ignore_index = True)

#Putting in latitude and longitude for all countries in data
#Used 'loc' data for most but had to manually input 36 of them because their info was not included or had formatting issues
for i in countries.index:
   for j in loc.index:
       if countries.at[i, "country"] == loc.at[j, "Country"]:
           countries.at[i, "lat"] = loc.at[j, "Latitude"]
           countries.at[i, "long"] = loc.at[j, "Longitude"]

#Calculates average age, average rank, and number of players for each country and updates columns in 'countries' dataframe.

for j in countries.index:
    totalAge = 0
    totalRank = 0
    count = 0
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "nationality"] == countries.at[j, 'country']:
            totalAge += data.at[i, "age"]
            totalRank += data.at[i, "overall"]
            count += 1

    countries.at[j,'avgAge'] = totalAge/count
    countries.at[j,'avgRank'] = totalRank/count
    countries.at[j,'numPlayers'] = count

#'countries' dataframe is tidied and complete!  
countries

Exploratory Analysis and Data Visualization¶

Now, it's time to explore whether there are any patterns between age, location, position, and rank!

Age)¶

First, let’s look at the presence of any patterns relating to a player’s age.

Age and Player Frequency¶

Let's look at the most common ages in the dataset by comparing age to the age's frequency.

In [219]:
#Age vs. freq
uniqueAges = set()
data

for i in data.index:
    if data.at[i, 'age'] not in uniqueAges:
        uniqueAges.add(data.at[i, 'age'])

print(len(uniqueAges))

df3 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["age", "freq"])
for age in uniqueAges:
    count = 0
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, 'age'] == age:
            count += 1
    df3 = df3.append({"age": age, "freq": float(count)}, ignore_index = True)

df3

#Makes scatter plot for age vs. frequency
ax = df3.plot.scatter(x = 'age', y = 'freq')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('Age vs. Age Frequency in FIFA 2021 Data')

Out[219]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Age vs. Age Frequency in FIFA 2021 Data')

In the graph above, we can see that the frequency of age is somewhat bell-shaped. That is, the most frequent ages fall roughly in the young to middle ages. As age gets much younger and much older, we see fewer amounts of players that age. The most frequent ages are around 22-28. We also see that the frequency of age is somewhat right-skewed because the age frequencies tamper off slightly more to the right.

#Regression for age vs. freq
x = np.linspace(15, 45, num=10)
y =  7.59796313e-01*x**3 + -7.43559176e+01 *x**2 + 2.28659637e+03*x + -2.11636650e+04
obj1 = plt.plot(x, y)
obj2 = plt.scatter(df3['age'], df3['freq'])
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('Age vs. Age Frequency Regression in FIFA 2021 Data')
plt.show()


def polyfit(x, y, degree):
    results = {}
    coeffs = np.polyfit(x, y, degree)
    p = np.poly1d(coeffs)
    #calculate r-squared
    yhat = p(x)
    ybar = np.sum(y)/len(y)
    ssreg = np.sum((yhat-ybar)**2)
    sstot = np.sum((y - ybar)**2)
    results['r_squared'] = ssreg / sstot
    
    print("Equation: ", coeffs[0],"x^3 + ", coeffs[1], "x^2 + ", coeffs[2], "x + ", coeffs[3])
    print("R^2:", results['r_squared'])

polyfit(df3['age'], df3['freq'], 3)

Equation:  0.7597963126698706 x^3 +  -74.35591764557223 x^2 +  2286.5963739538265 x +  -21163.665013402748
R^2: 0.9864034598179616

There is clearly a relationship between age and age frequency in the FIFA 2021 data shown in the regression above. If we were interested in seeing whether this pattern generalizes to all FIFA data, the next step would be to perfrom similar analyses on FIFA data from other years including prior as well as future years. If we see similar trends to the pattern here in the other data, then perhaps a generalization could be made about the relationship between age and age frquency in all FIFA data.

In [221]:
#Average age vs. continent
conts = ['Asia', 'Africa', 'South America', 'North America', 'Australia/Oceania', 'Europe']
df2 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["continent", "avgAge"])

for c in conts:
    contPlayerAges = np.array([])
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "continent"] == c:
            contPlayerAges = np.append(contPlayerAges, [data.at[i, "age"] ])

    sum = np.sum(contPlayerAges)
    num = np.size(contPlayerAges)
    meanAge = sum/num


    #np.median(contPlayerAges)
    df2 = df2.append({"continent": c, "avgAge": meanAge}, ignore_index = True)

#Makes bar graph
ax = df2.plot.bar(x='continent', y='avgAge', rot=10)
plt.xlabel('Continent')
plt.ylabel('Average Player Age')
plt.title('Average Player Age for Each Continent')

Average Age and Nationality¶

Let's now look at the average player age of each nationality. Below is a map with markers that represent the average age for each country. The marker color represents the age group of the average player age for each country. There are three classes of ages that are each shown in a different shade of green.
The lighest green represents the average age being between 17 and 25.
The middle shade of green represents average age being between 26 and 34.
The darker shade of green represents the average age being between 35 and 43 (only one country).

In [222]:
#Creates map to look at relationship between location and average age.

#marker color -> age group (ranges from 17-43)

m = folium.Map(location=[48, -5], zoom_start=2)
for i in countries.index:
    avgAge = countries.at[i, "avgAge"]

    if avgAge >= 17 and avgAge <= 25:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="lightgreen")).add_to(m)

    elif avgAge >= 26 and avgAge <= 34:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="green")).add_to(m)

    if avgAge >= 35 and avgAge <= 43:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="darkgreen")).add_to(m)
        
m

Looking at the map above, we see that the average age for most countries is around the mid age (26-34) shown in the middle shade of green. Although the majority of the countries have ages that fall in the middle ages, it is interesting to observe that there is a patch of countries that fall in the younger age group (17-25), shown in the lighter green color. There is cluster of lighter green markers in western Africa and in the middle of Africa. This shows that there is a larger presence of younger players aged 18-25 in Africa than other continents.

Location)¶

Nationality and Player Frequency¶

First, let's take a look at the frequency of players in the data from each country (nationality) by looking at them on a map.
The number of players included in the data is separated into 4 color groups on the map below.
The pink markers represent the number of players being between 0 and 373.
The orange markers represent the number of players being between 374 and 747.
The red markers represent the the number of players being between 748 and 1121.
The black markers represent the the number of players being between 1122 and 1496.

If you click on the markers, the number tells the number of players included in the data set for that country.

In [223]:
#Creates map to look at relationship between location and player frequency.

#marker color -> freq group (ranges from 1 to 1496)
m = folium.Map(location=[48, -5], zoom_start=2)
for i in countries.index:
    freq = countries.at[i, "numPlayers"]

    if freq >= 0 and freq <= 373:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = freq, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="pink")).add_to(m)

    elif freq >= 374 and freq <= 747:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = freq, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="orange")).add_to(m)

    elif freq >= 748 and freq <= 1121:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = freq, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="red")).add_to(m)

    elif freq >= 1122 and freq <= 1496:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = freq, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="black")).add_to(m)

In the bar graph above, we can see that Europe has the most amount of players represented in the FIFA 2021 data set by far. They have more than double the frequency compared to each of the other continents and also has more than all of the other continents combined. The continent with the next highest amount of players is South America. An important note to also keep in mind is the amount of countries included in each continent as well as continent population sizes. In the data refinement phase above, we created continent sets with the countries included in each continent. From those sets, you can get an idea of the amount of countries that each continent includes. You can see that Africa, Asia, and Europe have the most countries. Whereas, South America and Australia/Oceania have much less countries, with North America in the middle. What does this tell us? Well, for how few countries that are included in South America, they have a fairly high frequency of players represented. On the other hand, although Europe has a very high frequency of players represented, Europe also includes a lot of countries. Club Team and Player Frequency¶

Second, let's look at the club teams that have the most players represented in the data.

In [226]:
uniqueClubs = set()
#new dataframe to store summarized information about each club including number of players, average rank of players, and average age of players
clubs = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["club", "numPlayers", "avgRank", "avgAge"])
for i in data.index:
    if data.at[i, "team"] not in uniqueClubs:
        uniqueClubs.add(data.at[i, "team"])
        clubs = clubs.append({"club": data.at[i, "team"], "numPlayers": "-", "avgRank": "-",
                "avgAge": "-"}, ignore_index = True)


print("Number of clubs in data set:", len(uniqueClubs))
#Takes a while to run - about 3 min
for j in clubs.index:
    numPlayers = 0
    rankTotal = 0
    ageTotal = 0
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "team"] == clubs.at[j, "club"]:
            numPlayers += 1
            rankTotal += data.at[i, "overall"]
            ageTotal += data.at[i, "age"]
    avgRank = rankTotal / numPlayers
    avgAge = ageTotal / numPlayers
    clubs.at[j, "numPlayers"] = numPlayers
    clubs.at[j, "avgRank"] = avgRank 
    clubs.at[j, "avgAge"] = avgAge

Position)¶

The position abbreviations are as follows:

-GK - Goalkeeper  
-LB - Left Back      
-CB - Center Back    
-RB - Right Back    
-RWB - Right Wing Back    
-LWB - Left Wing Back    
-CDM - Center Defensive Midfield    
-CM - Center Midfield    
-CAM - Center Attacking Midfield     
-LM - Left Midfield    
-RM - Right Midfield    
-LW - Left Wing     
-RW - Right Wing    
-CF - Center Forward    
-ST - Striker

Some players play more than one position. To account for that, we will make additional rows for each additional position that the player plays.

In [228]:
#organizing data based on position
d2 = data.filter(["name", "age", 'overall', "position", "nationality"])
d3 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["name", "age", "rank", "position", "nationality"])

# reformat position coloumn to account for multiple positions played by one player by adding a new row per position in df3
for i, row in d2.iterrows():
    pos = d2.at[i, "position"]
    positions = pos.split('|')
    for pos in positions:
        newRow = {'name': d2.at[i, 'name'],'age': d2.at[i, "age"], 'rank': d2.at[i, "overall"], 'position': pos, 'nationality': d2.at[i, "nationality"]}
        d3 = d3.append(newRow, ignore_index = True)

    totalRank = 0
    for i in d3.index:
        if d3.at[i, "position"] == pos:
            count += 1
            totalAge += d3.at[i, "age"]
            totalRank += d3.at[i, "rank"]
    avgAge = totalAge/count
    avgRank = totalRank/count
    posData = posData.append({"position": pos, "freq": float(count), "avgAge": float(avgAge),

Position and Nationality¶

Let's take a look at the most common type of position (defense+goalkeeper, midfield, attack) for each country of player nationality.

In [233]:
countries['mostFreqPos'] = '-'
defense = set(['CB', 'GK', 'RB', 'LB', 'LWB', 'RWB'])
midfield = set(['RM', 'LM', 'CAM', 'CM', 'CDM'])
attack = set(['ST', 'CF', 'LW', 'RW'])
for i in countries.index:
    dc = 0
    mc = 0
    ac = 0
    maxPos = ""
    for j in d3.index:
        if d3.at[j, "nationality"] == countries.at[i, "country"]:
            if d3.at[j, "position"] in defense:
                dc += 1
            elif d3.at[j, "position"] in midfield:
                mc += 1
            elif d3.at[j, "position"] in attack:
                ac += 1

    max = np.max(([dc, mc, ac]))
    if max == dc:
        maxPos = "defense"
    elif max == mc:
        maxPos = "midfield"
    elif max == ac:
        maxPos = "attack"
    countries.at[i, "mostFreqPos"] = maxPos

Average Rank and Age¶

Now, let's take a look at the relationship between average age and rank.

In [237]:
#finds average rank for each age
uniqueAges = set()
for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "age"] not in uniqueAges: 
            uniqueAges.add(data.at[i, "age"])

print(len(uniqueAges))

allAgePlayerRanks = {}
ageAvgRank = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["age", "avgRank"])

for a in uniqueAges:
    AgePlayerRanks = np.array([])
    for i in data.index:
            if data.at[i, "age"] == a:
                AgePlayerRanks = np.append(AgePlayerRanks, [ data.at[i, "overall"] ])

    sum = np.sum(AgePlayerRanks)
    num = np.size(AgePlayerRanks)
    
    meanRanking = sum/num
    n = {a: meanRanking}
    allAgePlayerRanks.update(n)
    ageAvgRank = ageAvgRank.append({"age": float(a), "avgRank": meanRanking}, ignore_index = True)

ageAvgRank
ax = ageAvgRank.plot.scatter(x = 'age', y = 'avgRank')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Average Rank')
plt.title('Average Player Rank for Each Age in FIFA 2021 Data')
plt.show()

27

In the graph above, we see that the relationship between age and average rank for each age in the FIFA 2021 data set follows a parabola shape. That is, the middle ages tend to have the highest average ranks, and the much younger/older ages have lower ranks. This makes sense as some of the players we think about when talking about the best soccer players fall around the middle ages such as Lionel Messi (34) and Cristiano Ronaldo (36). Why might this be the case? This may be related to these players having sufficient experience (compared to younger players) while also carrying enough youth to be physically fit in performing well (compared to older players). Thus, the middle-aged players are able maintain a strong balance of experience and fitness.

Rank (top 50 ranked players) and Player Nationality¶

Let's now take a look at the relationship between rank and location. Let's see where the top 50 ranked players are from!

The main marker color represents the player's ranking. The darker blue represents the highest ranked players (rank 90 to 94), and the ligher blue represents the lower ranked players from the top 50 (rank 85 to 89).
The icon color represents the player's age. The lighter green represents the younger players (aged 17 to 25), the middle green shade represents the mid-older players (aged 26 to 34), and the darker green represents the oldest players (aged 35 to 43).
Clicking on a marker will display information about the particular player being represented: name, age, rank.

These results were surprsing as many would predict Europe to have the highest average player ranking. What may justify these findings? It is important to note and keep in mind the frquency of players in each continent (from above) as well because continents with a small amount of players may only have higher ranked players representing the country. Whereas, continents will a high amount of players in the data may have a larger variety and broader range of ranked players (Europe). This wider range would heavily impact the mean. The presence of any outliers would have an effect on the mean and may bring it down a bit. Whereas, continents will only higher ranked players may not have these low outliers or at least as many low outliers to bring the mean down.

Hypothesis Testing¶

1) Two Sample Z-Test for Mean¶

We are going to carry out a hypothesis test with significance level of .01 and also find a 99% confidence interval for the average rank of all FIFA soccer players aged 26-34 versus players not aged 26-34.

Let's begin with the hypothesis test. x̅ will be the average rank of players who are between ages 26-34 (middle ages from the data) in the FIFA 21 data, and y̅ will be the players who are between ages 17-25 and 35-43 (the rest of the player ages from the data set, youngest and oldest) from the FIFA 21 data. We will be testing to see whether the true average rank of all FIFA soccer players between ages 27-35 is higher than that of the rest of the players at .01 significance level.

First, we will need to organize our data into their correct group based on age.

In [243]:
midAge = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["player", "age", "overall"]) #middle ages
yoAge = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["player", "age", "overall"]) #younger older ages
for i in data.index:
    if data.at[i, "age"] >= 26 and data.at[i, "age"] <= 34:
        midAge = midAge.append({"player": data.at[i, "name"], "age": data.at[i, "age"], "overall": data.at[i, "overall"]}, ignore_index = True)
    else:
        yoAge = yoAge.append({"player": data.at[i, "name"], "age": data.at[i, "age"], "overall": data.at[i, "overall"]}, ignore_index = True)
In [244]:

Two Sample Z-Test Hypothesis Testing for Mean at .01 significance level

Null Hypothesis: mu1 - mu2 = 0
Alternate Hypothesis: mu1 - mu2 > 0
where mu1 is the true average rank of all FIFA soccer players aged 26-34 and mu2 is the true average rank of all FIFA soccer players aged anything other than 26-34.

Assume Null Hypothesis is true.

In [246]:
alpha = .01

testStatistic = (xBar - yBar - 0) / (np.sqrt( ((sd1**2)/m) + ((sd2**2)/n) ) )
print("Test Statistic =", testStatistic)

#P(Z > testStatistic)
pValue = 1 - (st.norm.cdf(testStatistic))
print("P-value =", pValue)

if pValue <= alpha:
    print("Reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.")
else:
    print("Do not reject null hypothesis.")

Test Statistic = 40.67337137934258
P-value = 0.0
Reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.

As per above, p-value = 0 and alpha = .01.
As p-value <= alpha, we will reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.

Based on the sample data (FIFA 21 data), there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the true average rank of all FIFA soccer players aged 26-34 is higher than the true average rank all FIFA soccer players not aged 26-34 at .01 significance level.

99% Confidence Interval¶

We will now find the 99% confidence interval for the difference in true average rank between all FIFA soccer players who are between ages 26-34 (middle ages from the data) and players who are not between 26-34 (representing the youngest and oldest players).

In [247]:
diffAvg = xBar - yBar
alpha = .01
criticalValue = NormalDist().inv_cdf((1- (alpha/2)))

marginOfError = criticalValue * np.sqrt( ((sd1**2)/m) + ((sd2**2)/n) )
ciLeft = diffAvg - marginOfError
ciRight = diffAvg + marginOfError
print("99% Confidence Interval = (",ciLeft,",",ciRight, ")")

99% Confidence Interval = ( 3.220961958201797 , 3.6565096468714 )

We are 99% confident that the difference in the true average rank between all FIFA soccer players who are between ages 26-34 (middle ages in the data) and all FIFA soccer players who are not between ages 26-34 (representing the youngest and oldest players) lies between (3.220961958201797, 3.6565096468714) at .01 level of significance.

2) Two Sample Z-Test for Proportion¶

We are going to carry out a hypothesis test with significance level of .01 and also find a 99% confidence interval for the difference in the true proportion of players with a European nationality in all of the higher (about top 10%) ranked FIFA soccer players versus the lower ranked (about bottom 90%).

We will begin with the hypothesis test.
p̂1 will be the proportion of the top 1798 (about 10% of 17981) ranked players in the FIFA 21 dataset who have European nationality, and p̂2 will be the proportion of the bottom 16183 ranked players in the FIFA 21 data set who have European nationality. We will be testing to see whether the true proportion of all FIFA players with a European nationality is higher amongst the top (about top 10%) ranked players than the lower (about bottom 90%) ranked players at .01 significance level.

First, we will need to organize our data into their correct group based on rank.

In [248]:
topRanked = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["player", "overall", "continent"])
bottomRanked = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["player", "overall", "continent"])

for i in data.head(1798).index:
    topRanked = topRanked.append({"player": data.at[i, "name"], "overall": data.at[i, "overall"], "continent": data.at[i, "continent"]}, ignore_index = True)

for i in data.tail(16183).index:
    bottomRanked = bottomRanked.append({"player": data.at[i, "name"], "overall": data.at[i, "overall"], "continent": data.at[i, "continent"]}, ignore_index = True)

Two Sample Z-Test Hypothesis Testing for Proportion at .01 significance level

Null Hypothesis: p1 - p2 = 0
Alternate Hypothesis: p1 - p2 > 0
where p1 is the true proportion of all top (about top 10%) FIFA soccer players with European nationality and p2 is the true proportion of all lower (about bottom 90%) FIFA soccer players with European nationality.

Assume Null Hypothesis is true.
We must check conditions for performing the hypothesis test. We will be ensuring the following conditions hold first.
mp̂1 >= 10 -> 1798(.6279) = 1128.9642
mq̂1 >= 10 -> 1798(.3721) = 669.0358
np̂2 >= 10 -> 16183(.5646) = 9136.9218
nq̂2 >= 10 -> 16183(.4354) = 7046.0782

In [251]:
alpha = .01

pHat = ((m/(m+n))*p1Hat) + ((n/(m+n))*p2Hat)
qHat = 1 - pHat

testStatistic = (p1Hat - p2Hat - 0) / ( np.sqrt(pHat*qHat*((1/m)+(1/n))) )

print("Test Statistic =", testStatistic)

#P(Z > testStatistic)
pValue = 1 - (st.norm.cdf(testStatistic))
print("P-value =", pValue)

if pValue <= alpha:
    print("Reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.")
else:
    print("Do not reject null hypothesis.")

Test Statistic = 5.146000661571044
P-value = 1.330492416240503e-07
Reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.

As per above, p-value = 0 and alpha = .01. As p-value <= alpha, we will reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.

Based on the sample data, there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the true proportion of players with a European nationality is higher amongst the top (about top 10%) FIFA soccer players than the lower (about bottom 90%) ranked FIFA players at .01 significance level.

99% Confidence Interval¶

We will now find the 99% confidence interval for the difference in the true proportion of players with a European nationality amongst the top (about 10%) ranked FIFA players and the lower (about bottom 90%) ranked FIFA players at .01 significance level.

In [252]:
diffp = p1Hat - p2Hat
alpha = .01

criticalValue = NormalDist().inv_cdf((1- (alpha/2)))

marginOfError = criticalValue * np.sqrt( ((p1Hat*(1-p1Hat))/m) + ((p2Hat*(1-p2Hat))/n) )
ciLeft = diffp - marginOfError
ciRight = diffp + marginOfError
print("99% Confidence Interval = (",ciLeft, ",",ciRight, ")")

99% Confidence Interval = ( 0.03228378271003379 , 0.09434637485172986 )

We are 99% confident that the difference in the true proportion of players with a European nationality amongst the top (about top 10%) ranked FIFA players and the lower (about bottom 90%) ranked FIFA players lies between (0.03228378271003379 , 0.09434637485172986) at .01 level of significance.

Machine Learning - Regression¶

Recall that when the relationship between age and average rank was analyzed above, there was a noticable trend in the scatter plot. The scatter plot had a parabolic shape. Let's perform quadratic regression on this relationship. We will examine the equation, R^2 value, the sum of squared error (SSE)/residual sum of squares (RSS), and see how it looks visually.

In [253]:
#Age vs average rank relationship

#Quadratic Regression
def polyfit(x, y, degree):
    results = {}
    coeffs = np.polyfit(x, y, degree)
    p = np.poly1d(coeffs)
    #calculate r-squared
    yhat = p(x)
    ybar = np.sum(y)/len(y)
    ssreg = np.sum((yhat-ybar)**2)
    sstot = np.sum((y - ybar)**2)
    sse = np.sum((y - yhat)**2)
    results['r_squared'] = ssreg / sstot
    print("Equation: ", coeffs[0],"x^2 + ", coeffs[1], "x + ", coeffs[2])
    print("R^2:", results['r_squared'])
    print("Sum of Squared Error (SSE):", sse)

polyfit(ageAvgRank['age'], ageAvgRank['avgRank'], 2)

#Graph
x = np.linspace(15, 45, num=10)
y =  -0.0363*x**2 + 2.4063*x + 29.7200
obj1 = plt.plot(x, y)
obj2 = plt.scatter(ageAvgRank['age'], ageAvgRank['avgRank'])
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Average Rank')
plt.title('Average Player Rank vs. Age Regression in FIFA 2021 Data')
plt.show()
plt.show()
 

Equation:  -0.036253841904561705 x^2 +  2.4062742558070718 x +  29.71995952655366
R^2: 0.7429066447637408
Sum of Squared Error (SSE): 66.26948622170035

As shown above, there is clearly a relationship between age and average player rank in the FIFA 2021 data from in the regression above. The R^2 value is fairly high, so it suggests that there is a relationship between them. If we were interested in seeing whether this pattern generalized to all FIFA data, the next step would be to perfrom similar analyses on FIFA data from prior years. If we see similar trends in the other data, then perhaps a generalization could be made about the relationship between age and average player rank which could be used for future predictions as well.

Ideas for More Analysis¶

-It would not only be interesting, but it would be important to compare the findings from FIFA's 2021 data to their data from previous (and future) years. For a few of the numeric relationships, we performed regressions on the patterns, so it would be important to run similar regressions on previous and future data to see if those trends and regressions can be generalized to most FIFA data or whether the patterns found from this analysis was unique and specific to this year's data.  
-On the same note, it would be interesting to see how any of the trends we found change throughout the years and analyze the patterns over time.     
-Once we have analyzed the data from several years, it would be important to look for any of the same trends. If there are consistent patterns corresponding to rank throughout the years, then it would be interesting to make a predictive rank model with those features that have consistent data.    
-Another idea that could be tested is the effect of having a few to many highly ranked players on a team and compare that to performance (both on club teams as well as international teams). The obvious hypothesis would be that teams with many highly ranked players would yield better team performance. However, this may not always be the case. For example, having too many highly ranked players that do not compliment each other may lead to conflicting styles and may not have the compounding effect that would be inferred.      
-Once data from past years have been analyzed, it would also be interesting to look at the results of tournament data and compare how the tournament data results compare to the analysis findings for the corresponding year. This could be conducted for both international tournamnets and club tournaments. For example, international tournaments include the World Cup, Euro Cup, the Olympics, Copa America, etc. Club tournaments include the UEFA Champions League.       
-It would also be interesting to look at the effect of players switching club teams by seeing whether there are drastic changes in the performance of the club that they switched to/from. This would require looking at data from many years in order to observe changes in the player's club team.

Link to FIFA data sets from other years: https://www.kaggle.com/search?q=fifa+player+dataset

Insights¶

For the FIFA 2021 data, we found the following key findings:

-Age and player rank have a parabolic relationship. That is, the middle ages of the ages represented in the data set, had the higher player ranks. The more younger and older rages in the data set had lower ranks. We saw this trend visually with a regression and also performed a two sample hypothesis test that supported these results. It found that ages 26-34 had a higher mean player rank than the rest of the players ages.  
-Most of the top ranked players have European nationality. There is a larger proportion of players that are from European countries in the top 10% ranked players than in the rest of the players (bottom 90%) in the data set. This was found using a two sample hypothesis test. While performing the test, it was found that over 62% of the top 10% ranked players are from Europe.   
-All of the top 15 club teams with the highest average player ranking are located in Europe. 
-By far, Europe had the most players represented (most of the players have European nationality).   
-The most common player ages represented in the data set were around ages 22-28. The player ages became less common for much younger and much older ages (following a bell-curve).
-Center back and center midfield were the most popular player positions in the data. The most players were listed as playing these positions, compared to the others.
-The average ages for the three groups of positions (defense, midfield, and attack) were all very similar (around 25-27) with defense being slightly older, followed by midfield, and then attack. 
-The position with the highest average player age was goalkeeper.

Conclusion¶

We now have a much better understanding of the information contained in the FIFA 2021 data set! We have comprehensively explored the various features of the data set including age, nationality (country and continent), club team, and position. We looked at the distribution of these features in the data set and the connections between these different features. In order to make stronger observations and to give statements regarding the patterns about FIFA data in general (not just from 2021), it will be necessary to analyze the FIFA data from prior years to see if the patterns we currently see can be generalized from finding similar trends those years as well. We will have to see if the insights above can be generalized from past data. If we do see similar trends over time, then the next step will focus on using it to help in making predictions about information regarding future players such as their rank and predicting how good future players will be in general.
